<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="40" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,796,1001]" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis box="[199,325,832,856]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">Etymology.</emphasis>
The feminine genus name is a combination of the genus names 
<taxonomicName box="[1086,1234,832,856]" class="Insecta" family="Chamaemyiidae" genus="Chamaemyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1086,1234,832,856]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">Chamaemyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1295,1396,833,856]" class="Insecta" family="Chamaemyiidae" genus="Leucopis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1295,1396,833,856]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">Leucopis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, to indicate the unexpected presence of 
<number box="[563,577,868,892]" pageId="1" pageNumber="40" value="2.0">2</number>
pairs of strong fronto-orbital setae, a character present in 
<taxonomicName box="[1239,1387,868,892]" class="Insecta" family="Chamaemyiidae" genus="Chamaemyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1239,1387,868,892]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">Chamaemyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other chamaemyiines, but only rarely in leucopines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="40" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,796,1001]" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis box="[199,313,941,964]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. As a monotypic genus, the diagnosis for the genus is identical to that of the single species. The key in 
<bibRefCitation author="Gaimari" box="[179,353,976,1000]" pageId="1" pageNumber="40" refString="Gaimari, S. D. (2010) Chamaemyiidae. Pages 997 - 1007, in: Brown, B. V., Borkent, A., Cumming, J. M., Wood, D. M., Woodley, N. E. &amp; Zumbado, M. (eds.), Manual of Central American Diptera. Volume 2. NRC Research Press, Ottawa, Canada, xvi + pp 715 - 1442" type="book chapter" year="2010">
Gaimari (
<number box="[286,345,976,1000]" pageId="1" pageNumber="40" value="2010.0">2010</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
aids the separation of this genus from all other New World genera.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
